Classification of Emotions in Texts

The goal of the project is the automatic classification of emotions in texts. The model will be trained on a dataset containing texts with numerical labels assigned to emotions:

  • sadness (0)
  • joy (1)
  • love (2)
  • anger (3)
  • fear (4)
  • surprise (5)

The final product will be a tool that enables the automatic recognition of the dominant emotion in any given text.

Thanks to automatic emotion recognition, large sets of product and service reviews can be quickly analyzed, allowing for the efficient identification of problems and positive aspects that deserve attention. This approach allows for faster responses to issues, improving the quality of customer service. The early detection of negative emotions can help prevent customer loss, while a deeper understanding of customer sentiment enables precise tailoring of offers to their needs.

Additionally, the tool can be used for monitoring comments and opinions, as well as for content personalization. As a result, it becomes possible to better understand customer needs and build trust, which ultimately leads to improved financial performance for the company.

Removing Stopwords

The most frequently occurring words in each subgroup are stopwords, which are not significant in the context of analysis. We will remove them to focus on words that truly stand out in each subgroup, allowing for a more accurate analysis and differentiation between categories.

To achieve this, we will create a preprocess function that:

  1. Convert all letters to lowercase

  2. Remove punctuation marks

  3. Remove stopwords

  4. Apply lemmatization to reduce words to their base forms.

In[79]:
nlp = spacy.load("en_core_web_sm")

def preprocess(text):
    # 1. Convert to lowercase
    text = text.lower()
    
    # 2. Removal of punctuations 
    text = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    
    # 3. Removal of stopwords and lemmatization
    doc = nlp(text)
    text = [token.lemma_ for token in doc if not token.is_stop]
    
    return " ".join(text)

Tokenization

In our case, we will use three models: SVM, LSTM, and Transformers. Each of these models has its own specifications regarding the types of input data they handle best, so we will utilize different types of tokenization. For SVM, we will use TF-IDF tokenization; for LSTM, we will use word indexing; and for Transformers, we will use the pre-trained TinyBERT model.

a) SVM

TF-IDF tekonizer

TF-IDF consists of two main components:

  • TF (Term Frequency): This is typically the number of occurrences of a word in a document divided by the total number of words in that document.
$$TF(t,d) = \frac{\text{The number of occurrences of the term } t \text{ in the document } d}{\text{Total number of words in document } d} $$
  • IDF (Inverse Document Frequency) - This measures the uniqueness of terms. Words that appear in many documents have a lower IDF value, indicating they are less significant (as they are more common), while words that occur in fewer documents have a higher IDF value, suggesting they are more unique.

$$IDF(t,D) = log\left(\frac{\text{Total number of documents in set } D }{\text{Number of documents containing the term } t} \right) $$

TF-IDF is simply the product of TF and IDF for a given word in a document.

$$TF-IDF = TF(t,d) * IDF(t)$$

Words that frequently appear in a given document but rarely in others will have a high TF-IDF value, indicating they are more significant for that particular document.

4. Dataset Split and Undersampling

Undersampling

Undersampling is a technique that reduces the size of the majority class in a data set to the size of the minority class.

In our case, the smallest class is 'surprise' (5). After splitting the dataset into training and testing sets, while maintaining the proportion of classes, we will randomly sample an equal number of observations from the remaining classes from the training set to obtain a balanced data set. Then, we will perform the analysis on both sets - the unbalanced and the balanced one.

Splitting the dataset into training and testing sets

80% of the data will be allocated to the training set, while the remaining 20% will be used for the testing set.

The 'stratify' parameter ensures that splitting the data into training and test sets preserves the proportions of label classes in the data. Whereas 'shuffle' shuffles the data before splitting to ensure randomness.

X_resampled_transformers, y_X_resampled_transformers = rus.fit_resample(train_data['preprocessed_text'].values.reshape(-1, 1), train_data['label'])

The reshape(-1, 1) method transforms a one-dimensional array into a two-dimensional matrix, which is required by fit_resample() since it expects the input data in a 2D format.

  • The -1 indicates that the number of rows will be automatically determined based on the number of examples.
  • The 1 signifies that each row will contain a single column (e.g., one text per row).

5. Modeling

a) SVM (Support Vector Machines)

Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a supervised machine learning algorithm that classifies data by finding the optimal line or hyperplane that maximizes the margin between different classes in an N-dimensional space.

In[105]:
classifier = LinearSVC(class_weight='balanced', dual=False)
classifier.fit(X_train_svm, y_train_svm) #Fitting the model to the training data
y_pred_class = classifier.predict(X_test_svm)
y_pred_class2 = classifier.predict(X_train_svm)

# Collecting metrics
acc_train_svm = round(metrics.accuracy_score(y_train_svm, y_pred_class2),4)

#print("Accuracy (train set): ", round(metrics.accuracy_score(y_train_svm, y_pred_class2),4))
print("Accuracy (test set): ", round(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test_svm, y_pred_class),4))

Accuracy (test set):  0.8835

The SVM (Support Vector Machine) model achieved an accuracy of 0.8835 on the test set. This means that the model correctly classified about 88.35% of the samples in the test set.

However, this is an imbalanced dataset, meaning the data is unevenly distributed across the classes, which may affect the result. The majority of the samples belong to classes 1 and 0, while class 5 has the fewest samples. This imbalance can lead to better model fit for more represented classes and worse for the less frequent ones. Therefore, we will also check other metrics like the F1-score and visualize our results using a Confusion Matrix.

Confusion Matrix (test set)

In[106]:

plt.show()

Y-axis (True Labels) shows the actual classes to which the test data belongs.

X-axis (Predicted Labels) shows the classes predicted by the model.

The diagonal values are correctly classified examples. The remaining values off the diagonal are classification errors, i.e. examples that the model predicted incorrectly. For example, cell(1,2) = 1959 means that 1959 examples of class 1 were incorrectly classified as class 2.

Classes 0 and 1 have the highest number of correct predictions, which is also due to their larger representation in the dataset. Classes 2, 3, 4, and 5, being less frequent, have lower values along the diagonal.

The largest model misclassifications occur between classes 1 and 2 and 4 and 5. Class 1(joy) is sometimes predicted as class 2(love) and vice versa, and class 4(fear) is sometimes predicted as class 5(surprise), which may suggest some similarities between these classes.

b) LSTM (Long short-term memory)

Long short-term memory (LSTM) is a type of recurrent neural network (RNN) aimed at dealing with the vanishing gradient problem present in traditional RNNs.

A common LSTM unit consists of a cell, an input gate, an output gate, and a forget gate.

In[115]:
EMBEDDING_DIM = 64

model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(MAX_NB_WORDS, EMBEDDING_DIM, input_length=X.shape[1]))

model.add(LSTM(64, dropout=0.3, recurrent_dropout=0.3))
model.add(Dense(6, activation='softmax'))
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

Training arguments configuration

Hugging Face provides many parameters for TrainingArguments, offering great flexibility in tuning the transfer learning model.

  • output_dir is the directory where model checkpoints and predictions are saved.
  • logging_dir is the directory where logs are saved.
  • logging_strategy is the strategy for logging training information.
    • 'no' means no logging during training.
    • 'epoch' means logging at the end of each epoch.
    • 'steps' means logging at the end of every logging_steps.
  • logging_steps is the number of steps between two logs. The default value is 500.
  • num_train_epochs is the total number of training epochs. The default value is 3.
  • per_device_train_batch_size is the batch size per GPU/TPU/CPU core for training. The default value is 8.
  • per_device_eval_batch_size is the batch size per GPU/TPU/CPU core for evaluation. The default value is 8.
  • learning_rate is the initial learning rate for the AdamW optimizer. The default value is 5e-5.
  • seed is used for reproducibility.
  • save_strategy is the strategy for saving checkpoints during training.
    • 'no' means do not save during training.
    • 'epoch' means save at the end of each epoch.
    • 'steps' means save at the end of every save_steps. 'steps' is the default value.
  • save_steps is the number of steps before saving two checkpoints. The default value is 500.
  • evaluation_strategy is the strategy for evaluation during training. It is useful for monitoring the model's performance while fine-tuning.
    • 'no' means no evaluation during training.
    • 'epoch' means evaluation at the end of each epoch, and the evaluation results will be printed at the end of each epoch.
    • 'steps' means evaluation and reporting at the end of every eval_steps. 'no' is the default value.
  • eval_steps is the number of steps between two evaluations if evaluation_strategy='steps'. By default, it takes the same value as logging_steps if not set.
  • load_best_model_at_end=True indicates that the best model will be loaded at the end of training. By default, this is set to False. When set to True, save_strategy and evaluation_strategy must be the same. If both arguments are 'steps', the value of save_steps must be a rounded multiple of eval_steps.
In[139]:
training_args = TrainingArguments( 
    output_dir="/kaggle/working/results",
    logging_dir='/kaggle/working/logs',
    logging_strategy='epoch',

)

Setting the evaluation metrics

Since our dataset is imbalanced, in addition to accuracy, we will use F1-score as the evaluation metric.

In[140]:
# List of evaluation metrics.
#evaluate.list_evaluation_modules()
In[141]:
# Function for calculating metrics.
def compute_metrics(eval_pred):
    accuracy_metric = evaluate.load("accuracy")
    logits, labels = eval_pred
    predictions = np.argmax(logits, axis=1)
    accuracy = accuracy_metric.compute(predictions=predictions, references=labels)
    f1 = f1_score(labels, predictions, average='weighted')
    return {
        'accuracy': accuracy['accuracy'],
        'f1': f1
    }
